// Semantic direction:
// async_file wraps OS file I/O with async reads and writes backed by the io_uring or thread pool.
// file_open_a opens with the given open_options_a; opt_create_new_a fails if the file exists.
// file_seek_a repositions the file cursor; file_len_a returns the current file size.
// file_sync_a flushes OS buffers to disk, ensuring durability.
// file_metadata_a returns size, type, permissions, and timestamps without opening the file.
// async_dir provides async directory creation, removal, and listing.
// dir_read_a returns an async stream of dir_entry items.
// dir_remove_all_a recursively removes a directory and all its contents.
// entry_file_type distinguishes files, directories, and symlinks.
// path_copy_a copies a file including its contents; path_rename_a is atomic on the same filesystem.
// temp_file_a creates a named or unnamed temporary file deleted on close.
// watch_a monitors a path for changes and produces watch_event_a items.
// debounce_watch filters rapid successive events into one per stable period.
// spawn_blocking_a runs a blocking function (legacy I/O, CPU work) on blocking_thread_pool.
// blocking_thread_pool is a separate pool of OS threads for blocking operations.
// run_blocking moves a closure to blocking_thread_pool and returns a future for its result.
// This prevents blocking calls from stalling the async reactor.

// Primitive flow:
// async file read: file_open_a("data.txt", read) -> file_read_a(file, buf)
//   io_uring: sqe(read, fd, buf) -> submit -> wait cqe -> return bytes
//   fallback: spawn_blocking_a(|| std::fs::read(path)) -> run_blocking -> future
// dir listing: dir_read_a("./src") -> async stream of dir_entry
//   for await entry in stream: if entry.metadata.is_file: process(entry.path)
// watch: watch_a("./src") -> stream of watch_event_a
//   on watch_modify: debounce -> trigger rebuild
// temp: temp_file_a() -> write data -> flush -> persist or discard on drop

// This defines async file operations: open, read, write, seek, sync,
// directory operations, path utilities, file watching, and blocking I/O offload.
